<br>
This has been irritating me lately, too.  I'm an Acrylia Studded capable tailor (161 and climbing), and even if I get good deals on the Superb Rockhopper Hides and Small Pieces of Acrylia, I constantly get people who want to buy, say, an Acrylia Studded Cloak, but don't want to pay what I paid to make it in the first place.  &quot;What?!  It's not worth that!&quot;<br>
<br>
I've started taking to telling them that if they bring me all the components themselves, I'll do it for free.  So far, not one has taken me up on that.<br>
<br>
It's depressing to see people selling some of these items at under the cost to produce.  I think some of these people are people who bought the items without having any idea what it actually cost to make; some others are people who have the cash to burn, anyway, and don't care.<br>
<br>
Acrylia tailoring is a problem for most of us.  Either we have to spend forever gathering the components, which are a) overcamped by Bazaar price speculators and b) relatively rare, or we have to buy them in the Bazaar for the best prices we can find them for.  This is a supply-demand problem.  Every tailor needs both the acrylia and the rockhopper hides.  Add to this that some smiths need acrylia, too.  On the other end, however, once a person has their cloak, their sleeves, their tunic, they don't need to buy anymore.  They're not consumables.  So as the demand for the components remains either the same or goes up, the demand for the product goes down.<br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong.  I believe this is all part of the natural cycle of the market, and I think claiming that someone's prices are &quot;too high&quot; or &quot;too low&quot; is ridiculous.  If they're able to sell their product at that price, then the price is &quot;just right&quot;.  However, no one can sell at a loss, so these things will, eventually, balance themselves out. <p>"Adjusting to an oppressive system cannot be the answer; in the last analysis, it is not we who need the therapy."<BR>
-Alan Sinfield, <u>The Wilde Century: Effeminacy, Oscar Wilde, and the Queer Moment</u><BR>
